<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
Collections were made from the hindgut of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kimmins" authorityYear="1941" class="Insecta" family="Nemouridae" genus="Protonemura" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Protonemura montana" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Protonemura montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kimmins nymphs, with a low infestation rate (2%). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leger &amp; Gauthier" authorityYear="1931" class="Kickxellomycetes" family="Orphellaceae" genus="Orphella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Orphella coronata" order="Orphellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Zygomycota" rank="species" species="coronata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Orphella coronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported from diverse localities in Europe, (e.g. France (
<bibRefCitation author="Leger, L" journalOrPublisher="Travaux du Laboratoire d' Hydrobiologie et de Pisciculture de l'Universite de Grenoble" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="67 - 72" refId="B18" refString="Leger, L, Gauthier, M, 1931. Orphella coronata n. g., n. sp. Entophyte parasite des larves de Nemurides. Travaux du Laboratoire d' Hydrobiologie et de Pisciculture de l'Universite de Grenoble 23: 67 - 72" title="Orphella coronata n. g., n. sp. Entophyte parasite des larves de Nemurides." volume="23" year="1931">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Léger">Leger</normalizedToken>
and Gauthier 1931
</bibRefCitation>
, 1932), Norway (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" author="White, MM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="891 - 910" refId="B72" refString="White, MM, Lichtwardt, RW, 2004. Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae. Mycologia 96: 891 - 910, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" title="Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" volume="96" year="2004">White and Lichtwardt 2004</bibRefCitation>
), Spain (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1335 - 1347" refId="B66" refString="Valle, LG, Santamaria, S, 2005. Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella. Mycologia 97: 1335 - 1347, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" title="Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" volume="97" year="2005">Valle and Santamaria 2005</bibRefCitation>
), Portugal (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="748 - 759" refId="B59" refString="Valle, LG, 2013a. New and rare Harpellales from Portugal and northwestern Iberian Peninsula: discovering the hidden mycobiota of Galicia-Tras-os-Montes region. Mycologia 105: 748 - 759, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" title="New and rare Harpellales from Portugal and northwestern Iberian Peninsula: discovering the hidden mycobiota of Galicia-Tras-os-Montes region." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" volume="105" year="2013 a">Valle 2013a</bibRefCitation>
) and Italy (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="712 - 727" refId="B67" refString="Valle, LG, Rossi, W, Santamaria, S, 2013. New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy. Mycologia 105: 712 - 727, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" title="New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" volume="105" year="2013">Valle et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
)). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leger &amp; Gauthier" authorityYear="1931" class="Kickxellomycetes" family="Orphellaceae" genus="Orphella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Orphella coronata" order="Orphellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Zygomycota" rank="species" species="coronata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Orphella coronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be the rarest species of the genus in the Bulgarian streams surveyed, although many potential hosts were dissected from the Struma River. Fortunately, the only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kempny" authorityYear="1898" class="Insecta" family="Nemouridae" genus="Protonemura" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Protonemura" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Protonemura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
infested specimen was carrying various mature thalli of 
<taxonomicName genus="O." lsidName="O. coronata" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="coronata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">O. coronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so that we could observe trichospores and the typical heterothallically-formed helicoidal zygospores typical for the species, these being very important to discern and identify possible cryptic species (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1335 - 1347" refId="B66" refString="Valle, LG, Santamaria, S, 2005. Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella. Mycologia 97: 1335 - 1347, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" title="Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" volume="97" year="2005">Valle and Santamaria 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="589 - 606" refId="B68" refString="Valle, LG, Rossi, W, Santamaria, S, 2014. Orphella intropus (Kickxellomycotina), a new insect endosymbiont with an unusual perforating holdfast system and other trichomycetes from Italy. Mycologia 106: 589 - 606, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" title="Orphella intropus (Kickxellomycotina), a new insect endosymbiont with an unusual perforating holdfast system and other trichomycetes from Italy." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" volume="106" year="2014">Valle et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.2018.1448198" author="White, MM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" refId="B73" refString="White, MM, Valle, LG, Lichtwardt, RW, Siri, A, Strongman, DB, William, RT, Gause, WJ, Tretter, ED, 2018. New species and emendations of Orphella: taxonomic and phylogenetic reassessment of the genus to establish the Orphellales, for stonefly gut fungi with a twist. Mycologia 110(1): 147-178. https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.2018.1448198" title="New species and emendations of Orphella: taxonomic and phylogenetic reassessment of the genus to establish the Orphellales, for stonefly gut fungi with a twist. Mycologia 110 (1): 147 - 178." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.2018.1448198" year="2018">White et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Bulgarian specimens show the typical thallus with a bifurcate basal cell and allantoid trichospores (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">22</figureCitation>
), measuring 36-41 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.5-6.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in our collections, slightly smaller than previously reported (35-48 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
according to Valle &amp; Santamaria 2004). Terminal cell measures 22-25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. Zygospores (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">23</figureCitation>
) in our collections measure 26-32 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, also somewhat smaller than those reported in the description of the zygospores (30-35 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
according to Valle &amp; Santamaria 2004), but likely attributable to intraspecific variation; in fact, just a couple of thalli were found producing sexual spores in our collections and about 5 producing trichospores.
</paragraph>
